01:27:15.620 --> 01:27:18.260
My name is Dan Carpenter.

01:27:18.260 --> 01:27:21.020
And I teach in the government
department here at Harvard,

01:27:21.020 --> 01:27:24.410
and I direct the social sciences
academic ventures faculty

01:27:24.410 --> 01:27:27.450
director at Radcliffe.

01:27:27.450 --> 01:27:29.700
And I want to offer--
before giving some thanks--

01:27:29.700 --> 01:27:35.010
two reflections on today, one
personal and one professional.

01:27:35.010 --> 01:27:37.200
I learned so much today.

01:27:37.200 --> 01:27:42.000
This isn't my field
of study, primary.

01:27:42.000 --> 01:27:44.040
But what I learned about
actually my own past

01:27:44.040 --> 01:27:48.060
in listening to stories about
Georgetown and other places

01:27:48.060 --> 01:27:51.550
was a way of putting together
parts of a larger story.

01:27:51.550 --> 01:27:54.450
I grew up in a small
town, a very small town

01:27:54.450 --> 01:28:00.750
of about 800 people in Northern
Michigan, entirely white.

01:28:00.750 --> 01:28:04.980
I then went to college at
Georgetown in Washington DC.

01:28:04.980 --> 01:28:08.070
I then went to graduate school
at the University of Chicago,

01:28:08.070 --> 01:28:10.027
the south side of Chicago.

01:28:10.027 --> 01:28:12.360
And then my three academic
jobs have been at Princeton--

01:28:12.360 --> 01:28:13.680
which we heard a lot
about yesterday--

01:28:13.680 --> 01:28:15.846
University of Michigan, and
now, of course, Harvard.

01:28:19.260 --> 01:28:22.320
I learned today that
every place along the way

01:28:22.320 --> 01:28:28.630
of my own academic journey was
spent at an institution that

01:28:28.630 --> 01:28:37.570
supported me, housed me,
educated me, credentialed me,

01:28:37.570 --> 01:28:41.650
and that owed its
existence, or its endowment,

01:28:41.650 --> 01:28:46.080
or its buildings to
slavery, and/or which

01:28:46.080 --> 01:28:49.380
sat amidst, but
comfortably isolated

01:28:49.380 --> 01:28:52.110
from structures of
racial oppression

01:28:52.110 --> 01:28:54.390
right in its neighborhood.

01:28:54.390 --> 01:28:57.000
And I had limited, partial
awareness of these stories

01:28:57.000 --> 01:28:57.810
today--

01:28:57.810 --> 01:28:59.790
before today, excuse me.

01:28:59.790 --> 01:29:01.680
I knew some about
Georgetown's history

01:29:01.680 --> 01:29:03.430
when I was there as a student.

01:29:03.430 --> 01:29:06.180
I knew a bit about
Chicago's environment

01:29:06.180 --> 01:29:10.350
and what Ta-Nehisi Coates
referred to as Rob Sampson's

01:29:10.350 --> 01:29:16.080
important research on racial
segregation in Chicago.

01:29:16.080 --> 01:29:19.450
I knew something-- many
thanks to Sven Beckert

01:29:19.450 --> 01:29:22.890
about the history of Harvard.

01:29:22.890 --> 01:29:24.450
But today gave me
the opportunity

01:29:24.450 --> 01:29:28.350
to weave these threads
together into a fabric, which

01:29:28.350 --> 01:29:32.730
like a wampum belt or maybe
even a [INAUDIBLE] cloth,

01:29:32.730 --> 01:29:33.660
I could read.

01:29:33.660 --> 01:29:35.970
And what a sobering
reading that is

01:29:35.970 --> 01:29:39.270
to know that my entire-- just
my entire educational career

01:29:39.270 --> 01:29:43.320
has been spent at a lineage of
institutions supported, funded,

01:29:43.320 --> 01:29:48.080
subsidized, structured
by slavery themselves.

01:29:48.080 --> 01:29:49.830
And that is one that
I'm going to continue

01:29:49.830 --> 01:29:51.810
to read in the months,
and years, and weeks

01:29:51.810 --> 01:29:55.626
to come, just as a person,
as a student, as a scholar.

01:29:55.626 --> 01:29:57.750
And I hope that today's
conference has given others

01:29:57.750 --> 01:30:01.710
the ability to read anew
our past, individual

01:30:01.710 --> 01:30:04.530
and collective, our president,
and our universities,

01:30:04.530 --> 01:30:07.400
and what they ought to
do with their futures.

01:30:07.400 --> 01:30:09.800
I hope, as a professional
remark, and second,

01:30:09.800 --> 01:30:10.790
that we can move--

01:30:10.790 --> 01:30:13.520
as Ta-Nehisi Coates
said we should--

01:30:13.520 --> 01:30:17.360
to forms of reparation,
and that we universities

01:30:17.360 --> 01:30:21.170
think more thoroughly, and
elaborately, and specifically

01:30:21.170 --> 01:30:23.480
about what to do next.

01:30:23.480 --> 01:30:25.010
Let me say as a
political scientist

01:30:25.010 --> 01:30:27.710
that I don't think that
conversation about slavery

01:30:27.710 --> 01:30:29.210
in the university--

01:30:29.210 --> 01:30:34.420
either interrogating its past or
discussing its future repair--

01:30:34.420 --> 01:30:37.450
can advance without
consideration of the state.

01:30:37.450 --> 01:30:42.070
And here, I am so thankful
that Madame Taubira just stole

01:30:42.070 --> 01:30:45.430
my point 10 minutes ago,
and said it far better

01:30:45.430 --> 01:30:48.520
than I'm about to
convey it to you now--

01:30:48.520 --> 01:30:51.640
the state by which I mean our
government, our political,

01:30:51.640 --> 01:30:56.050
judicial, and administrative
institutions, our laws.

01:30:56.050 --> 01:31:01.060
As the histories inform us,
slavery prevailed and profited,

01:31:01.060 --> 01:31:05.880
in part, because laws defined
bodies of color as property.

01:31:05.880 --> 01:31:08.190
And the state
enforced those laws

01:31:08.190 --> 01:31:12.210
and legitimated those
bodies rendered as assets.

01:31:12.210 --> 01:31:17.550
Expanding the geographies
of slavery with armed force,

01:31:17.550 --> 01:31:19.890
and with treaties
and other strategies

01:31:19.890 --> 01:31:22.920
of Native American
dispossession,

01:31:22.920 --> 01:31:26.980
structuring the contracts
by which slaves were sold,

01:31:26.980 --> 01:31:30.210
including the
Georgetown sale of 1838,

01:31:30.210 --> 01:31:33.750
and were executed
and made enforceable.

01:31:33.750 --> 01:31:39.480
Enslavement was
government, I think, maybe.

01:31:39.480 --> 01:31:41.730
Beyond the history, it seems
difficult to think about

01:31:41.730 --> 01:31:45.870
repair, given the enormous
weight of slavery and its

01:31:45.870 --> 01:31:48.930
legacies-- that Mr.
Coates talked about

01:31:48.930 --> 01:31:50.310
in today's keynote--

01:31:50.310 --> 01:31:52.560
without considering
the role of powers

01:31:52.560 --> 01:31:55.940
that can possibly bear
some of that weight.

01:31:55.940 --> 01:31:59.060
Not just the resources but the
authority of our governments

01:31:59.060 --> 01:32:01.880
and their ability-- like that
of universities-- to host

01:32:01.880 --> 01:32:04.820
and structure free
dialogue must be

01:32:04.820 --> 01:32:06.980
brought to any repair effort.

01:32:06.980 --> 01:32:10.290
Now, exactly how that
enlistment of the state occurs,

01:32:10.290 --> 01:32:13.070
of course, is something
probably for another conference

01:32:13.070 --> 01:32:14.090
altogether.

01:32:14.090 --> 01:32:17.030
And invite those
far better equipped

01:32:17.030 --> 01:32:22.350
and more knowledgeable than I
am to advance that discussion.

